[4] New York (Rockland county)
Date: Fri 2 Nov 2018
Source: Newsline, Patch report [abridged, edited]
https://newsline.com/2018/11/03/measles-outbreak-more-cases-more-clinics-in-rockland/


Rockland county health officials have added another free vaccine clinic as they grapple with the widening measles outbreak. With 46 cases of measles confirmed and 9 more suspected, officials consider "all of Rockland essentially exposed."

During these clinics, the Health Department and Refuah Health Center will be offering non-immune residents who are 6 months of age and older one dose of MMR vaccine at no cost.

Usually, children get their 1st measles vaccine at 12-15 months, but because of the outbreak health officials are urging that babies get their 1st MMR shot now, as younger children are more likely to get sicker.

Dr Patricia Schnabel Ruppert, Commissioner of the Rockland County Department of Health said at a press conference [Tue 30 Oct 2018], 2 children have already been hospitalized from this outbreak, and one is in intensive care.

Upcoming free measles, mumps, rubella (MMR) vaccine clinics are set for [locations listed at the source URL above.] People will be checked before entering to make sure they are not sick.

In addition, ALL schools within the village of New Square plus ANY school with less than a 70 percent MMR vaccination rate within Spring Valley and Monsey (the geographical area affected by the measles outbreak) will be required to keep un- or under-vaccinated students home until 21 days have passed since the last confirmed measles case in Rockland.

It could be months, officials acknowledged.

That's 16 schools with more than 1000 students.

This is in addition to the letter issued on [18 Oct 2018], to schools that were attended by students with confirmed cases of measles, requiring that un- or under-vaccinated students remain home.

So far, 2100 people have gotten vaccinated at the free clinics, officials said.

[Byline: Lanning Taliaferro]

